      __Note: if you have previously run this notebook and have already saved a dataset with variables added, etc. you can skip straight to section 2.7, where you can re-load that dataset. For larger datasets, this may save a little time. However, there is nothing wrong with simply repeating these initial steps each time.__  
      ​
      We may have multiple subcorpora with the same variables; here we load them so we can access them both separately and combined into a single larger corpus. (If we have just a single corpus, this just gives us two different ways to address the same corpus.)
      ​
      In subsequent steps, we will generally work with the single combined dataframe only. However, it is easy to replace any reference to `df` by `sub_dfs[corpusname]` (where corpusname should, in turn, be replaced by an actual sub-corpus name).

      1. Load corpus or corpora¶

      Note: if you have previously run this notebook and have already saved a dataset with variables added, etc. you can skip straight to section 2.7, where you can re-load that dataset.       #### 2.2. Create dummy variables from count variables
      ​
      Add dummy variables (with a value of 0 or 1) corresponding to our count variables. These are, in general, the variables counting the occurrences of each of our search term categories, along with any features we defined.
      ​
      To keep naming simple, we rename all the count variables to get the extension `_count`, so the dummy version can get the original name of the variable.

      2.2. Create dummy variables from count variables¶

      Add dummy variables (with a value of 0 or 1) corresponding to our count variables. These are, in general, the variables counting the occurrences of each of our search term categories, along with any features we defined.

      ### 3. Collapse to daily, monthly, etc. levels
      ​
      Often we would like aggregate data by time period, rather than at the individual article level. 
      Most commonly we do this by day or month.

      3. Collapse to daily, monthly, etc. levels¶

      Often we would like aggregate data by time period, rather than at the individual article level. Most commonly we do this by day or month.

      In [83]:
       
      # Reduce to daily averages: group by day, then take means and add a count column
      ​
      # Group by day
      df_byday = df.drop(['Publication',], axis=1).set_index('Date').groupby(pd.Grouper(freq='D'))
      # Collapse by taking averages and adding a count variable indicating number of articles that month
      df_bydayX = df_byday.aggregate(np.mean).reset_index().join(df_byday.size().reset_index(name='nrarticles').drop('Date', axis=1))
      df_bydayX = df_bydayX.set_index('Date')
      . . .
      In [84]:
       
      # Reduce to monthly averages: group by month, then take means and add a count column
      ​
      # Group by month
      df_bymonth = df.drop(['Publication',], axis=1).set_index('Date').groupby(pd.Grouper(freq='M'))
      # Collapse by taking averages and adding a count variable indicating number of articles that month
      df_bymonthX = df_bymonth.aggregate(np.mean).reset_index().join(df_bymonth.size().reset_index(name='nrarticles').drop('Date', axis=1))
      df_bymonthX = df_bymonthX.set_index('Date')

      #### 7.1. Define functions to locate particular values in the corpus

      We define functions to look for values in our various data columns.

      7.1. Define functions to locate particular values in the corpus¶

      We define functions to look for values in our various data columns.

      The find_text function is particularly useful for locating specific phrases in longer texts.

      In [ ]:
       
      def find_val(row, targetvar, targetval):
          """Identify particular values in a given variable column."""
          return 1 if row[targetvar] == targetval else 0
      ​
      ​
      def find_text(row, textvar, targettext, capsmatter=False):
          """Identify particular (sub)strings in a textual column.
          
          Note that this is a quick-and-dirty search, 
          which does not take into account word boundaries!
          """
          if capsmatter:
              return 1 if targettext in row[textvar] else 0
          else:
              return 1 if targettext.lower() in row[textvar].lower() else 0
